A065001.name: a(n) = (presumed) number of palindromes in the 'Reverse and Add!' trajectory of n, or -1 if this number is not finite.

A065002.name: Integers m such that A064992(m) = A064992(m+1).

A065004.name: 100 written in base n, or -1 if such a representation does not exist.

A065005.name: Integers for which the periodic part of the continued fraction for the square root of n begins with 2.

A065006.name: Integers for which the periodic part of the continued fraction for the square root of n begins with 3.

A065007.name: Integers for which the periodic part of the continued fraction for the square root of n begins with 4.

A065008.name: Integers for which the periodic part of the continued fraction for the square root of n begins with 5.

A065009.name: Integers for which the periodic part of the continued fraction for the square root of n begins with 6.

A065010.name: Integers for which the periodic part of the continued fraction for the square root of n begins with 7.

A065011.name: Integers for which the periodic part of the continued fraction for the square root of n begins with 8.

A065012.name: Integers for which the periodic part of the continued fraction for the square root of n begins with 9.

A065013.name: Integers for which the periodic part of the continued fraction for the square root of n begins with 10.

A065015.name: Sum divides product: number of integer solutions (w,x,y,z), w >= x >= y >= z > 0, to the equation w*x*y*z = n*(w+x+y+z).

A065016.name: Working in base 2, replace n with the concatenation of its prime factors (without repetition).

A065017.name: Primes of the form p*q + p + q, where (p, q=p+2) are twin primes.

A065018.name: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} sigma(d)^2.
formula: Dirichlet convolution of A072861 and A000012. Dirichlet g.f.: zeta^2(s)*zeta^2(s-1)*zeta(s-2)/zeta(2s-2). - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 03 2011
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ 5 * Zeta(3)^2 * n^3 / 6. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 01 2019

A065019.name: Let phi be the golden number {1+sqrt(5)}/2 (A001622), let phi(n) be the number phi written in base 10 but truncated to n decimal digits. Sequence gives number of 1's at the beginning of the continued fraction expansion of phi(n).
formula: The value of lim n -> infinity a(n)/n is log(10)/2/log(phi)=2.3924...

A065020.name: Coefficients of irreducible polynomials over GF(3) listed in lexicographic order.

A065022.name: Composite n such that the sums of the composite numbers up to n, +/- 1, are twin primes.

A065023.name: Number of states in minimal automaton that recognizes biquanimous numbers in base n.

A065024.name: Number of n-digit biquanimous numbers in base 10 allowing leading zeros.

A065025.name: Consider biquanimous numbers that exclude 0's; sequence gives number of n-digit non-biquanimous numbers - number of n-digit biquanimous numbers.

A065026.name: a(1) = 1; for n>1, a(n) = smallest number that is not a sum or product of any subset of the numbers a(1) to a(n-1).

A065027.name: a(n) is the smallest k > 0 such that n^k < k!.
formula: It appears that L(n) < a(n) - n e + log(sqrt(2 Pi n)) < 1/2, where L(n) = -1/2 + o(1), and L(n) > -0.53 for all n. - _Robert Israel_, Oct 28 2016 (In other words, a(n) - n e + log(sqrt(2 Pi n)) < 1/2 for all n, and there is some function L(n) = -1/2 + o(1) such that -0.53 < L(n) < a(n) - n e + log(sqrt(2 Pi n)) for all n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Nov 04 2016)

A065028.name: Integers which when written in French contain an odd number of vowels.

A065029.name: Period length of the continued fraction for sqrt(2)*n (A064848) is 2.

A065030.name: Period length of the continued fraction for sqrt(5)*n is 2.

A065031.name: In the decimal expansion of n, replace each odd digit with 1 and each even digit with 2.

A065033.name: 1 appears three times, other numbers twice.

A065036.name: Product of the cube of a prime (A030078) and a different prime.
formula: Solutions of the equation tau(n^3)=5*tau(n). - _Paolo P. Lava_, Mar 15 2013

A065038.name: Values of Recamán's sequence A005132 at start of n-th segment (see A064492).

A065039.name: If n in base 10 is d_1 d_2 ... d_k then a(n) = d_1 + d_1d_2 + d_1d_2d_3 + ... + d_1...d_k.
formula: a(n) = sum( k>=0, floor(n/10^ k)) = n+A054899(n). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 03 2002
a(n)=10/9*n+O(log(n)), a(n+1)-a(n)=O(log(n)); this follows from the inequalities below.
a(n)<=(10*n-1)/9; equality holds for powers of 10.
a(n)>=(10*n-9)/9-floor(log_10(n)); equality holds for n=10^m-1, m>0.
a(n) = sum(d_(k)*RU(k+1),k=0..nod(n)-1), with the notation nod(n)and d_k given in a comment above, and RU(k)is the repunit (10^k-1)/9 (k times 1). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, May 04 2010

A065040.name: Triangle T(m,k): exponent of the highest power of 2 dividing binomial coefficient binomial(m,k).
formula: The n-th term a(n) is equal to the binomial coefficient binomial(m,k), where m = floor((1+sqrt(8*n+1))/2) - 1 and k = n - m(m+1)/2. Also a(n) = g(m) - g(k) - g(m-k), where g(x) = Sum_{i=1..floor(log_2(x))} floor(x/2^i), m = floor((1+sqrt(8*n+1))/2) - 1, k = n - m(m+1)/2. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, May 05 2007
T(m,k) <= log_2 m, for m > 0. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Mar 26 2013
a(n) * A047999(n) = 0 and a(n) + A047999(n) > 0 for all n.

A065042.name: Numbers k such that prime(k) + pi(k) is a prime.

A065043.name: Characteristic function of the numbers with an even number of prime factors (counted with multiplicity): a(n) = 1 if n = A028260(k) for some k then 1 else 0.
formula: a(n) = A001222(2n) mod 2. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 22 2013
G.f.: Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/(1 - x^n) = Sum_{n>=1} x^(n^2)/(1 - x^n). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 25 2017

A065044.name: Start of the first run of exactly n consecutive primes, none of which are twin primes.

A065045.name: Continued fraction expansion of the constant Product_{k>=0} (1 + 1/2^(2k))^(1/2) (A065445).

A065046.name: Numbers k such that prime(k) - pi(k) is a prime.

A065047.name: Primes which when written in base 2 and prepended with a 1 produce a prime.

A065048.name: Largest unsigned Stirling number of the first kind: max_k(s(n+1,k)); i.e., largest coefficient of polynomial x*(x+1)*(x+2)*(x+3)*...*(x+n).
formula: For n in the interval [A309237(k)-1, A309237(k+1)-2], a(n) = |Stirling1(n+1,k)|. - _Max Alekseyev_, Jul 17 2019

A065049.name: Odd primes of incorrect parity: number of 1's in the binary representation of n (mod 2) == 1 - (n mod 3) (mod 2). Also called isolated primes.

A065050.name: Prime numbers in the triangle of Eulerian numbers.

A065051.name: Let R(n) = n-th term of Recamán's sequence A005132; write R(n) = q*n + r with 0 <= r < n; sequence gives values of q.

A065052.name: Let R(n) = n-th term of Recamán's sequence A005132; write R(n) = q*n + r with 0 <= r < n; sequence gives values of r.

A065053.name: Lengths of intervals between special points in Recamán's sequence A005132.

A065054.name: Value of remainder r (see A065052) at start of n-th interval between special points in Recamán's sequence A005132.

A065055.name: Number of subtraction steps in n-th interval between special points in Recamán's sequence A005132.

A065056.name: Partial sums of Recamán's sequence A005132.

A065058.name: Number of paths to T(n,n,n) with T(i,j,k)=  0 if j>i or k>j and T(i,j,k) = T(i-1,j,k) + T(i,j-1,k) + T(i,j,k-1) and T(i,j,0) = 1.

A065059.name: Primes p such that prime(p) + pi(p) is a prime.

A065060.name: Primes p such that prime(p) - pi(p) is a prime.

A065061.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) - tau(n) is a prime.

A065062.name: Numbers k such that A065608(k) = A065608(k+1).

A065063.name: Numbers k such that A065608(k) is a square.

A065064.name: Numbers k such that A065608(k) = A065608(k+2).

A065065.name: Number of noncrossing connected graphs with nodes on a circle having n edges.
formula: G.f. satisfies: A(x) = x*(1+3*A(x)+4*A(x)^2+A(x)^3). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Nov 12 2014

A065066.name: Triangle T(n,k) read by rows of partially ordered sets ("posets") with n unlabeled nodes and k maximal elements (0 <= k <= n).

A065068.name: Number of fixed polyominoes with n cells of which no four are equally spaced on a straight line.
formula: a(n) = 0 for n >= 143. - _Jan Kristian Haugland_, Apr 28 2020

A065069.name: Numbers n such that Fibonacci(n) is not squarefree, but for all proper divisors k of n, Fibonacci(k) is squarefree.

A065071.name: Minimum number of identical bricks of length 1 which, when stacked without mortar in the naive way, form a stack of length >=n.

A065072.name: Number of ways to tile a square of side 2n by dominoes (rectangles of size 2 X 1 or 1 X 2) is 2^n * a(n)^2 (see A004003).
formula: a(n) ~ exp(G*(2*n + 1)^2/(2*Pi)) / (2^((n-1)/2) * (1 + sqrt(2))^(n + 1/2)), where G is the Catalan's constant A006752. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Apr 14 2020, updated Dec 30 2020

A065073.name: n-th prime + sum of digits of n-th prime.

A065074.name: Near-repunit primes that contain the digit 0.

A065075.name: Sum of digits of the sum of the preceding numbers.

A065076.name: a(0) = 0, a(1) = 1, a(n) = (sum of digits of a(n-1)) + a(n-2).

A065077.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,m) = C[n,m,m] where C[i,j,k] is the 3-dimensional Catalan pyramid defined by C[0,0,0]=1 and C[i,j,k]=0 if j>i or k>j and C[i,j,k]=C[i-1,j,k]+C[i,j-1,k]+C[i,j,k-1].

A065078.name: Triangle read by rows: a(n,m) = T[n,m,m] where T[i,j,k] is the 3-dimensional pyramid defined by T[n,m,0]=1 and T[i,j,k]=0 if j>i or k>j and T[i,j,k]=T[i-1,j,k]+T[i,j-1,k]+T[i,j,k-1].

A065079.name: Primes > 3 for which the alternating bit sum (A065359) is not equal to 1 or 2.

A065080.name: Denominator of Sum_{k=1..n} d(k)/k, where d() = A000005().
formula: Sum_{k=1..n} A000005(k)/k = A060436(n)/a(n) ~ log(n)^2/2 + 2*gamma*log(n) + gamma^2 - 2*gamma_1, where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620 and gamma_1 is the first Stieltjes constant A082633. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Aug 30 2018

A065081.name: Alternating bit sum (A065359) for n-th prime p: replace 2^k with (-1)^k in binary expansion of p.

A065082.name: Numbers n such that ( the period of continued fraction for square root of n )^3 = n.

A065083.name: The least k such that precisely n near-repunit primes can be formed from (10^k-1)/9 by changing one digit from 1 to 0.

A065084.name: Smallest prime having alternating bit sum (A065359) equal to n.

A065085.name: Smallest prime having alternating bit sum (A065359) equal to -n, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A065086.name: Number of n-digit biquanimous numbers in base 10 not allowing leading zeros.

A065087.name: a(n) = A000166(n)*binomial(n+1,2).
formula: a(n) = n * (n+1) * (a(n-1)/(n-1) + (-1)^n/2) for n > 1 - _Seiichi Manyama_, Jun 24 2018
E.g.f.: exp(-x)*x^2*(3 - 2*x + x^2)/(2*(1 - x)^3). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jun 25 2018

A065089.name: Volume (multiplied by 3) of polyhedron formed by points (i,j,k) in Z^3 with i^2+j^2+k^2 = n^2.

A065090.name: Natural numbers which are not odd primes: composites plus 1 and 2.

A065092.name: Primes with property that when written in base two complementing any single bit yields a composite number.

A065093.name: Convolution of A000010 with itself.
formula: Sum_{k=1..n} phi(k)*phi(n+1-k), where phi is Euler totient function (A000010).

A065094.name: a(1) = 1, a(n+1) is the sum of a(n) and floor( arithmetic mean of a(1) ... a(n) ).

A065095.name: a(1) = 1, a(n+1) is the sum of a(n) and ceiling( arithmetic mean of a(1) ... a(n) ).

A065096.name: Sums of lists produced by a variant of the iteration that produces the Catalan numbers: start with 0 and at each iteration replace each integer k with the list 0,1,...,k-1,k,k+1,k,k-1,...,1,0 and let a(n) be the sum of the resulting (flattened) list after n iterations.
formula: a(0) = 0 and, for n > 0, a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} A001003(k)*A001003(n+1-k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 27 2004

A065097.name: a(n) = ((2n+1)+(2n-1)-1)!/((2n+1)!*(2n-1)!).
formula: a(n) = C(2n)/2 where C(n) is the Catalan number A000108. - _David Callan_, Jun 01 2006
O.g.f.: ((cata(sqrt(x)) + cata(-sqrt(x)))/2 -1)/2, with the o.g.f. cata(x) of the Catalan numbers. See the W. Lang comment above. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jan 05 2012
a(n) = A001448(n) / (4*n + 2) if n>0. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 25 2014
O.g.f. is Revert( x*(1 + x)/(1 + 2*x)^4 ). - _Peter Bala_, Dec 01 2015

A065098.name: Sum of reciprocals of terms in period of continued fraction for sqrt(n) is an integer.

A065099.name: Weight 5 level 11 cusp form with complex multiplication by Q(sqrt(11)) and trivial character.
formula: G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (11 t)) = 11^(5/2) (t/i)^5 f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t). - _Michael Somos_, Jun 08 2007

a(n) is multiplicative with a(11^e) = 121^e, a(p^e) = (1 + (-1)^e) / 2 * p^(2*e) if p == 2, 6, 7, 8, 10 (mod 11), a(p^e) = a(p) * a(p^(e-1)) - p^4 * a(p^(e-2)) if p == 1, 3, 4, 5, 9 (mod 11) where a(p) = y^4 - 4 * p*y^2 + 2 * p^2 and 4*p = y^2 + 11 * x^2. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 08 2007

A065100.name: a(n+2) = 9*a(n+1) - a(n), a(0) = 3, a(1) = 27.
formula: a(n) = 9*a(n-1) - a(n-2) (with a(0)=3, a(1)=27). - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 07 2010

A065104.name: Numbers n such that for no m between n^2 and (n+1)^2 - 1 is it true that A003285(m)=A003285(m+1).

A065105.name: Numbers not expressible as a product of Fibonacci numbers.

A065106.name: Smallest Fibonacci index to produce a factor p^2 (for primes p).

A065107.name: Start of the permutation of the primes in the order in which p^2 first appears as a factor of a number in the Fibonacci sequence.

A065108.name: Positive numbers expressible as a product of Fibonacci numbers.
formula: As _Charles R Greathouse IV_ recently remarked, it would be good to have an asymptotic formula for this sequence. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jul 22 2012

A065109.name: Triangle T(n,k) of coefficients relating to Bezier curve continuity.
formula: For n > 0, T(n, k) = 2*T(n-1, k) - T(n-1, k-1). - _Gerald McGarvey_, May 29 2005
p(n,m,k) = (-1)^m*multinomial(n - m - k, m, k); t(n,m) = Sum_{k=0..n} (-1)^m*multinomial(n - m - k, m, k). - _Roger L. Bagula_, Sep 12 2008

A065110.name: If n = D0*10^0 + D1*10^1 + D2*10^2 + .. + Dk*10^k define f(n) = D0*0^10 + D1*1^10 + D2*2^10 + .. + Dk*k^10 (e.g. if n = 421 then f(n) = 4*2^10 + 2*1^10 + 1*0^10 = 4098). Sequence gives values of n such that f(n) is divisible by n.

A065111.name: Dead-end primes in "The Prime Number Maze.".

A065112.name: Smallest prime whose decimal expansion ends (nontrivially) with the n-th prime; or 0 if no such prime exists.

A065113.name: Sum of the squares of the n-th and the (n+1)st triangular numbers (A000217) is a perfect square.

A065114.name: Sum of terms in the period of continued fraction for sqrt(n) (A010340) is an square.

A065115.name: Least k such that the sum of terms in period of continued fraction for sqrt(k) is n.

A065116.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) +- tau(n) are primes.

A065117.name: Primes such that prime(p) +- pi(p) are simultaneously prime.

A065118.name: Numbers which are 19 times the sum of their digits.

A065119.name: n-th cyclotomic polynomial is a trinomial.

A065121.name: Least m such that maximal palindrome in period of continued fraction for sqrt(m) is n-th row of Pascal's triangle; or 0 if no such number exists.

A065123.name: Primes which, although they have correct parity, are not in the prime number maze.

A065124.name: a(n) = (sum of digits of a(n-2)) + a(n-1); a(0) = 0 and a(1) = 1.

A065125.name: Numbers n such that the sums of the odd and even aliquot parts of n both divide n.

A065127.name: Nonsquares with number of prime factors equal to twice the number of distinct prime factors.
formula: n = prod( p(i)^e(i)) i in [1, k] => sum( e(i)), i in [1, k] == 2k

A065128.name: Number of invertible n X n matrices mod 4 (i.e., over the ring Z_4).

A065129.name: a(n) is the least m such that m/A003285(m) = n, or 0 if no such m exists.

A065131.name: Arithmetic mean of first n terms of A001414 is an integer.
formula: A025281(n)/n is integer, where A025281(n+1)=A025281(n)+A001414(n) and A001414 is sum of primes dividing n (with repetition).

A065132.name: Arithmetic mean of first n terms of A008472 is an integer.
formula: Also, integers n that divide A024934(n).
Prime terms are listed in A143851.

A065133.name: Remainder when n-th prime is divided by the number of primes not exceeding n.
formula: a(n) = prime(n) mod pi(n) = A000040(n) mod A000720(n), n > 1.

A065134.name: Remainder when n is divided by the number of primes not exceeding n.

A065135.name: Numbers n such that p(n) = pi(n)*k + 1 for some k.
formula: Solutions to Mod[A000040(x), A000720(x)]=1. Values satisfying A065133(x)=1

A065136.name: Numbers n such that n = pi(n)*k + 1 for some k.

A065137.name: Sum of digits of n plus sum of cubes of digits of n.

A065138.name: Numbers that are equal to the sum of their digits plus the sum of cubes of their digits.

A065139.name: Numbers n such that the sum of prime(n) and pi(n) is divisible by n.
formula: Solutions to pi(x) + prime(x) = A000720(x) + A000040(x) = 0 (mod x).

A065140.name: a(n) = 2^n*(2*n)!.
formula: Hypergeometric generating function, in Maple notation: 1/sqrt(1-8*x), i.e., a(0)=1, a(n)=round(evalf(subs(x=0, n!*diff(1/(sqrt(1-8*x)), x$n)))), n=1, 2,... Integral representation as n-th moment of a positive function on a positive half-axis: a(n)=int(x^n*exp(-sqrt(x/2))/(2*sqrt(2*x)), x=0..infinity), n=0, 1, ....
G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - 4*x*(k+1)*(2*k+1)/(4*x*(k+1)*(2*k+1) + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 07 2013

A065141.name: a(n) = (n+1)*2^n*(2*n)!.
formula: Integral representation as n-th moment of a positive function on a positive half-axis, in Maple notation: a(n)=int(x^n*1/8*exp(-1/(sqrt(2))*sqrt(x))*(x+sqrt(2)*sqrt(x))/x, x=0..infinity), n=0, 1...

Hypergeometric generating function, in Maple notation: exp(4*x)*(BesselI(0, 4*x)+4*x*BesselI(0, 4*x)+4*x*BesselI(1, 4*x)), i.e. a(0)=1 and a(n)= evalf(limit(n!^2*diff(exp(4*x)*(BesselI(0, 4*x)+4*x*BesselI(0, 4*x)+4*x*BesselI(1, 4*x)), x$n), x=0)), n=1, 2...

A065142.name: a(n) = 2^n*(n+1)*(3*n)!.
formula: Integral representation as n-th moment of a positive function on a positive half-axis, in Maple notation: a(n)=int(x^n*(1/36*(2^(2/3)*x^(1/3)+4)*exp(-1/2*2^(2/3)*x^(1/3))*2^(2/3)/x^(2/3)), x=0..infinity), n=0, 1...

A065143.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} stirling2(n,k)*(1+(-1)^k)*2^k/2.
formula: Representation as a sum of an infinite series: a(n) = exp(2)*Sum_{k = 0..infinity} ((2*k)^n*2^(2*k)/(2*k)!) - sinh(2)*sum_{k = 0..infinity}(k^n*2^k/k!), for n >= 0.
a(n) ~ n^n * cosh(2*exp(r)-2) / (r^n * (exp(n) * sqrt(4*exp(2*r)*r^2/n + 1-n+r))), where r is the root of the equation -2*exp(r)*r*tanh(2-2*exp(r)) = n.
a(n) = (Bell_n(2) + Bell_n(-2))/2, where Bell_n(x) is n-th Bell polynomial. - _Vladimir Reshetnikov_, Nov 01 2015

A065144.name: Smallest prime containing the n-th square in decimal notation.

A065145.name: Smallest prime that begins with the n-th square in decimal notation.

A065146.name: Numbers n such that the arithmetic, geometric and harmonic means of phi(n) and sigma(n) are all integers.
formula: a = (phi(n)+sigma(n))/2, g = sqrt(phi(n)*sigma(n)), h = (2*phi(n)*sigma(n))/(phi(n)+sigma(n)) = g^2/a are all integers; phi() = A000010(), sigma() = A000203().

A065148.name: Nonprimes m such that phi(m)*sigma(m) is divisible by m+1.

A065149.name: Composite numbers m such that phi(m)*sigma(m) is divisible by m-1.

A065150.name: Numbers k such that the harmonic mean of phi(k) and sigma(k) is an integer.
formula: G^2 mod A = 0, where G^2 = A000010(m)*A000203(m), A = (A000010(m) + A000203(m))/2; harmonic mean = (G^2)/A is integer.

A065153.name: Numbers for which the cototient of the totient is equal to the  totient of the cototient.
formula: Numbers n such that phi(n) - phi(phi(n)) = phi(n - phi(n)) or A000010(A051953(m)) = A051953(A000010(m)).

A065154.name: Numbers for which the cototient of the totient is strictly less than the totient of the cototient.
formula: Numbers n such that phi(n) - phi(phi(n)) < phi(n - phi(n)) or A051953(A000010(n)) < A000010(A051953(n)).

A065155.name: Numbers whose cototient of totient is strictly greater than totient of cototient.
formula: Numbers n such that phi(n) - phi(phi(n)) > phi(n - phi(n)) orA051953(A000010(n)) > A000010(A051953(n)).

A065156.name: Numbers n such that some Lucas number (A000204) is divisible by n.
formula: Equals {1,2,4} union {p^e | p in A140409 and e > 0} union {2*p^e | p in A140409 and e > 0} union {4*p | p in A053032} union {4*p*q | p, q in A053032}. - _A.H.M. Smeets_, Sep 20 2020

A065157.name: Table of binary string substitutions: a(i,j) is obtained by substituting i for each 1-bit in j.

A065158.name: Table of reduced binary string substitutions: a(i,j) is obtained by substituting i for each 1-bit in j, then dividing by i.

A065159.name: Binary string self-substitutions: a(n) is obtained by substituting n for each 1-bit in binary expansion of n.
formula: a(n)=z(n, n) with z(u, v) = if u=0 then 0 else if u mod 2 = 0 then z(u/2, v)*2 else z([u/2], v)*A062383(v)+v. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 15 2004

A065352.name: Smallest m such that C(2m,m) is divisible by (m+n)!/m!.
formula: C(2m, m)=A*((m+1)(m+2)...(m+n-1)(m+n)); a(n) is the smallest such m belonging to n: a(n)=Min(m; Mod(A000984(m), (m+n)!/m!)=0)

A065353.name: Decimal representation of palindromes extracted from the Golden String using ever increasing Fibonacci-style subdivisions.

A065354.name: Decimal representation of binary palindromes extracted from the Golden String using ever-increasing Lucas-style subdivisions.

A065356.name: Final digits of A065355(n) (in reverse order) for sufficiently large n.

A065357.name: a(n) = (-1)^pi(n) where pi(n) is the number of primes <= n.

A065358.name: The Jacob's Ladder sequence: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} (-1)^pi(k), where pi = A000720.

A065359.name: Alternating bit sum for n: replace 2^k with (-1)^k in binary expansion of n.

A065360.name: Alternating sum of "negabits". Replace (-2)^k with (-1)^k in negabinary expansion of n.

A065361.name: Rebase n from 3 to 2. Replace 3^k with 2^k in ternary expansion of n.

A065362.name: Rebase n from 4 to 2. Replace 4^k with 2^k in quaternary expansion of n.
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n/4) if n == 0 (mod 4); otherwise, a(n) = a(n-1) + 1. - _Clark Kimberling_, Aug 03 2012

A065363.name: Sum of balanced ternary digits in n. Replace 3^k with 1 in balanced ternary expansion of n.

A065364.name: Alternating sum of balanced ternary digits in n. Replace 3^k with (-1)^k in balanced ternary expansion of n.

A065365.name: Replace 3^k with 2^k in balanced ternary expansion of n.

A065366.name: Replace 3^k with (-2)^k in balanced ternary expansion of n.

A065367.name: Replace 3^k with (-3)^k in balanced ternary expansion of n.

A065368.name: Alternating sum of ternary digits in n. Replace 3^k with (-1)^k in ternary expansion of n.

A065369.name: Replace 3^k with (-3)^k in ternary expansion of n.
formula: a(3*k+m) = -3*a(k)+m for 0 <= m < 3. - _Chai Wah Wu_, Jan 16 2020

A065370.name: The next smallest pair of numbers is taken so that a(2n-1)/a(2n) converges to e = exp(1).

A065371.name: a(1) = 1, a(prime(i)) = prime(i) - i for i > 0 and a(u * v) = a(u) * a(v) for u, v > 0.

A065373.name: Number of iterations of A065371 starting at n until 1 is reached.

A065374.name: Smallest k such that f(f(...f(k))) > 1, where f(k) = A065371(k) is iterated n times.

A065375.name: The next smallest pair of numbers is taken so that a(2n-1)/a(2n) converges to sqrt(2).

A065376.name: Primes of the form p + k^2, p prime and k > 0.

A065377.name: Primes not of the form p + k^2, with p prime and k > 0.

A065378.name: Primes p such that p^2 is a palindromic square.

A065379.name: Palindromic squares with a prime root.

A065380.name: Primes of the form p + 2^k, p prime and k >= 0.
formula: A078687(A049084(a(n))) > 0; A091932 is a subsequence. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, May 07 2006

A065381.name: Primes not of the form p + 2^k, p prime and k >= 0.
formula: A078687(A049084(a(n))) = 0; subsequence of A118958. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, May 07 2006

A065382.name: Number of primes between n(n+1)/2 (exclusive) and (n+1)(n+2)/2 (inclusive).

A065385.name: Numbers m at which value of cototient function (A051953) reaches a new record: cototient(m) > cototient(k) for all k < m.
formula: a=0; s=0; Do[s=n-EulerPhi[n]; If[s>a, a=s; Print[n]], {n, 1, 10000}]

A065386.name: Successive record values of the cototient function (A051953).

A065388.name: Record values for sigma(m) + phi(m): sum of sigma and totient is larger than for any previous number.

A065389.name: Numbers n such that sigma(phi(n)) sets a new record, i.e., sigma(phi(m)) > sigma(phi(k)) for all k < m numbers.
formula: Numbers at which A000203(A000010(n)) = A062402(n) reaches a new maximal value.

A065390.name: Peak values reached by A062402 at the sites listed in A065389.

A065391.name: Numbers n such that A062401(n) = phi(sigma(n)) is increasing; i.e., A062401(n) represents a new peak, so that A062401(n) > A062401(k) for all k < n.

A065392.name: a(n) = A062401(A065391(n)): phi(sigma(m)) peak values for m's (listed in A065391) at which those peaks are first reached.

A065393.name: Sigma(phi(m)) - phi(sigma(m)) is increasing at these values of m.

A065394.name: Increasing values of A065395: a(n) = A065395(A065393(n)).

A065395.name: Commutator of sigma and phi functions.

A065396.name: Primes of the form p + k*(k+1) / 2, p prime and k > 0.

A065397.name: Primes which have no representation p + k*(k+1) / 2, with p prime and k > 0: A000040-Complement of A065396.

A065398.name: Fibonacci numbers whose digits sum to a prime.

A065399.name: a(n) is the greatest integer m such that (1) written in base n it is also readable as if it is in factorial base and (2) this factorial base value is smaller than or equal to m.

A065400.name: a(n) is the greatest integer m such that (1) written in factorial base it is also readable as if it is in base n and (2) this base-n value is greater than or equal to m.
formula: a(n) = A065399(n) with its base-n expansion interpreted in factorial base. - _Charlie Neder_, Jun 12 2019

A065401.name: Number of normal play partisan games born on or before day n.

A065402.name: Number of normal play partisan games born on day n.

A065403.name: Primes of the form sigma(m^2) where m is a composite number ordered by values m.

A065404.name: Squares of composite numbers k such that sigma(k) (sum of divisors of k, A000203) is a prime.

A065405.name: Composite numbers k such that the sum of the divisors of k^2 is a prime.

A065406.name: Mersenne prime exponents (A000043) which are also Sophie Germain primes (A005384).

A065407.name: Number of levels in lattice formed by normal play partisan games born on day n.

A065408.name: Squares whose digits sum to a prime.

A065409.name: Fennessey-Larcombe-French sequence.
formula: a(n) = 2^n*Sum_{k=0..n} (4*k^2-2*k-1)/(2*k-1)*binomial(n, k)*binomial(2*n-2*k, n-k)*binomial(2*k, k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jun 02 2005

A065410.name: Number of labeled, rooted, binary trees with internal nodes labeled from {1, ...,n} and leaves labeled from {0,1} such that for any path from the root to a leaf, the internal nodes receive distinct labels. In other words, the number of decision trees on n Boolean variables.

A065411.name: Fibonacci numbers whose digits sum to a square.

A065413.name: Number of positive solutions to "numbers that are n times their number of binary 1's".

A065414.name: Decimal expansion of rank 2 Artin constant Product_{p prime} (1-1/(p^3-p^2)).

A065417.name: Exponents in expansion of rank-2 Artin constant product(1-1/(p^3-p^2), p=prime) as a product zeta(n)^(-a(n)).
formula: a(n) ~ r^n / n, where r = A092526 = 1.465571231876768... - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jun 13 2020

A065418.name: Decimal expansion of Hardy-Littlewood constant Product_{p prime >= 5} (1-(3*p-1)/(p-1)^3).
formula: The constant equals Product_{n>=2} (zeta(n)*(1-2^-n)*(1-3^-n))^-A027376(n). - _Michael Somos_, Apr 05 2003

A065419.name: Decimal expansion of Hardy-Littlewood constant Product_{p prime >= 5} (1-(6*p^2-4*p+1)/(p-1)^4).

A065420.name: Triangle T(n,k) = binomial(n+2,k+1)*(binomial(n+2,k+1)-1), n >=0, 0 <= k <= n.

A065421.name: Decimal expansion of Viggo Brun's constant B, also known as the twin primes constant B_2: Sum (1/p + 1/q) as (p,q) runs through the twin primes.

A065422.name: If n|a(n) then a(n+1) = a(n)/(highest power of n that divides a(n)), otherwise a(n+1) = n*a(n); a(0) = 1.

A065423.name: Number of ordered length 2 compositions of n with at least one even summand.
formula: a(n+2)=sum{k=0..n, gcd(n, k) mod 2}; - _Paul Barry_, May 02 2005

A065424.name: Catalan-like formula: a(n) = binomial(6m, 3m+1)/(9m+6).
formula: G.f.: A*sqrt((A+1)*(1+9*A)) where A=x*(1+9*A)^3*(1+A). - _Mark van Hoeij_, Nov 16 2011

A065425.name: Smallest odd prime greater than n such that the decimal expansion of its base n conversion is also prime.

A065426.name: Incrementally larger terms in the continued fraction (A065645) for the twin prime constant (A005597).

A065428.name: Numbers n such that no x^2 mod n is prime.

A065429.name: Number of permutations of {1..n} which contain 3 consecutive terms in increasing order.

A065430.name: Order of commutator subgroup of GL(2,Z_n) (invertible 2 X 2 matrices mod n - sequence A000252).
formula: For odd n: a(n) = A000056(n) i.e. the commutator subgroup is SL(2, Z_n);
for even n: a(n) = A000056(n) / 2 (it has index 2 in SL(2, Z_n)).

A065431.name: Continued fraction expansion of Hardy-Littlewood constant (A065419) Product_{p prime >= 5} (1-(6*p^2-4*p+1)/(p-1)^4).

A065432.name: Triangle related to Catalan triangle: recurrence related to A033877 (Schroeder numbers).

A065433.name: Numbers n such that there exist x, y with n^2 = x! + y!.

A065434.name: Decimal expansion of imaginary part of 2nd nontrivial zero of Riemann zeta function.

A065435.name: a(3) = 2, a(4) = 3; for n > 4, a(n) = {a(n-2)}+{a(n-1)}, where {a} means largest prime <= a.
formula: a(n) = A007917(a(n-2)) + A007917(a(n-1)). - _Jonathan Vos Post_, Jul 10 2008

A065437.name: Smallest base relative to which the n-th prime is palindromic.

A065439.name: Numbers n such that s[n], p[n] and s[n]+p[n] are all prime numbers, where s[n] is the sum of digits of n and p[n] is the product of digits of n.

A065440.name: a(n) = (n-1)^n.
formula: E.g.f.: x/(T(x)*(1-T(x))) (where T(x) is Euler's tree function, the E.g.f. for n^(n-1)) (see A000169).

A065441.name: Sum of absolute values of terms in n-th row of A065432.

A065442.name: Decimal expansion of Erdős-Borwein constant Sum_{k>=1} 1/(2^k - 1).
formula: Fast computation via Lambert series: 1.60669515... = Sum_{n>=1} x^(n^2)*(1+x^n)/(1-x^n) where x=1/2. - _Joerg Arndt_, May 24 2011

A065444.name: Decimal expansion of 9*Sum_{k>=1} 1/(10^k-1).
formula: Equals 9 * sum(k>=1, (1+x^k)/(1-x^k) * x^(k^2) ) where x = 1/10.  This allows fast computation for this and similar sequences (involving sum(k>=1, x^k/(1-x^k) for some x < 1 ). - _Joerg Arndt_, Apr 25 2016

A065447.name: Concatenation of 1, 00, 111, 0000, ..., n 1's (if n is odd) or n 0's (if n is even).

A065448.name: Numbers k such that k is congruent to the product of its digits modulo the sum of its digits.

A065450.name: Make an infinite chessboard from the squares in the first quadrant; sequence gives number of squares a knight can reach in n moves starting at the origin.
formula: Conjectures: G.f.: [1+6x^2+4x^3-4x^4-2x^5+2x^6]/[(1+x)*(1-x)^3]. For n>3, partial sums of A047356. - _Ralf Stephan_, Mar 06 2004

The second conjecture "For n>3, partial sums of A047356" is also true. From the last possible move, we can either move back to the second last possible move or to b(n)=A047883(n) new squares. So a(n) = a(n-2)+b(n). For n>6, b(n)=7(n-1)+4=A017029(n-1). But a number of the form 7n+4 is naturally the sum of two consecutive terms in A047356 (4=1+3,11=3+8,18=8+10, ...). The conjecture follows. - _Vim Wenders_, Apr 12 2008

A065452.name: Decimal expansion of imaginary part of 3rd nontrivial zero of Riemann zeta function.

A065453.name: Decimal expansion of imaginary part of 4th nontrivial zero of Riemann zeta function.

A065454.name: Let the k-th harmonic number be H(k) = Sum_{i=1..k} 1/i = P(k)/Q(k) = A001008(k)/A002805(k); sequence gives values of k such that Q(k) = Q(k+1).

A065455.name: Number of (binary) bit strings of length n in which no even block of 0's is followed by an odd block of 1's.

A065456.name: Number of functions on n labeled nodes whose representation as a digraph has two components.
formula: a(n) ~ (n-1)! * exp(n)*(log(n/2) + gamma)/4, where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant (A001620). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 05 2013

A065457.name: Period of the flip-riffle shuffle function on a deck of 2n cards.

A065458.name: Number of inequivalent (ordered) solutions to a^2 + b^2 + c^2 + d^2 = n^2.

A065459.name: Number of inequivalent (ordered) solutions to n^2 = sum of 5 squares of integers >= 0.

A065460.name: Number of inequivalent (ordered) solutions to n^2 = sum of 6 squares of integers >= 0.

A065461.name: Number of inequivalent (ordered) solutions to n^2 = sum of 7 squares of integers >= 0.

A065462.name: Number of inequivalent (ordered) solutions to n^2 = sum of 8 squares of integers >= 0.

A065463.name: Decimal expansion of Product_{p prime} (1 - 1/(p*(p+1))).
formula: Equals lim_{m->oo} (2/m^2)*Sum_{k=1..m} rad(k), where rad(k) = A007947(k) is the squarefree kernel of k (Cohen).
Equals lim_{m->oo} (2/m^2)*Sum_{k=1..m} uphi(k), where uphi(k) = A047994(k) is the unitary totient function (Sitaramachandrarao and Suryanarayana).
Equals lim_{m->oo} (1/log(m))*Sum_{k=1..m} 1/psi(k), where psi(k) = A001615(k) is the Dedekind psi function (Sita Ramaiah and Suryanarayana).

A065464.name: Decimal expansion of Product_{p prime}(1 - (2*p-1)/p^3).
formula: Equals A065463 divided by A013661. - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 22 2011
Equals A065473 divided by A065480. - _R. J. Mathar_, May 02 2019
Equals lim_{m->oo} (1/m) * Sum_{k==1..m} (phi(k)/k)^2, where phi is the Euler totient function (A000010). - _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 12 2021

A065465.name: Decimal expansion of Product_{p prime} (1 - 1/(p^2*(p+1))).
formula: Sum_{n>=1} phi(n)/(n*J(n)) = (this constant)*A013661 with phi()=A000010() and J() = A007434() [Cohen, Corollary 5.1.1]. - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 11 2011

A065469.name: Decimal expansion of Product_{p prime} (1 - 1/(p^2-1)).
formula: Product of A013661 by A065474. - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 26 2011

A065472.name: Decimal expansion of Product_{p prime} (1 - 1/(p+1)^2).
formula: Equals lim_{n->oo} (Pi^2/(3*n^2*log(n))) * Sum_{k=1..n} A145388(k). - _Amiram Eldar_, May 14 2019

A065473.name: Decimal expansion of the strongly carefree constant: Product_{p prime} (1 - (3*p-2)/(p^3)).
formula: The constant c in Sum_{k<=x} mu(k)^2 * 2^omega(k) = c * x * log(x) + O(x), where mu is A008683 and omega is A001221, and in Sum_{k<=x} 3^omega(k) = (1/2) * c * x * log(x)^2 + O(x*log(x)) (see Tenenbaum, 2015). - _Amiram Eldar_, May 24 2020

A065475.name: Natural numbers excluding 2.
formula: Partial sums of A097330. G.f.: (1+x-x^2)/(1-x)^2. - _Paul Barry_, Aug 05 2004
a(n) = n+1 for n>1, a(n) = a(n-1)+1 for n>2. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Mar 13 2016

A065477.name: Decimal expansion of constant 5 * Pi^2 * A065476 / 48.

A065478.name: Decimal expansion of Product_{p prime} (1 - p/(p^3-1)).

A065483.name: Decimal expansion of totient constant Product_{p prime} (1 + 1/(p^2*(p-1))).

A065484.name: Decimal expansion of product(1 + p/((p-1)^2*(p+1))), p prime >= 2).
formula: Also defined as: Sum_{m>=1} 1/(m*A000010(m)). See Weisstein link.

A065485.name: Decimal expansion of Murata's constant Product_{p prime}(1 + 1/(p-1)^2).
formula: Equals lim_{k->oo} (1/pi(k)) * Sum_{p prime, p <= k} (p-1)/phi(p-1), where pi(k) = A000720(k) and phi(k) = A000010(k) (Murata, 1991). - _Amiram Eldar_, Jul 31 2020

A065489.name: Decimal expansion of Product_{p prime} (1 + 1/(p^2+p-1)).
formula: 1 divided by A065463. - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 26 2011

A065490.name: Exponents in expansion of constant A065463 as Product_{n>1} zeta(n)^(-a(n)).
formula: a(n) ~ (-1)^n * phi^n / n, where phi = A001622 = (1+sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 09 2019

A065491.name: Exponents in expansion of constant A065479 as a product zeta(n)^(-a(n)).

A065492.name: Exponents in expansion of constant A065480 as a product zeta(n)^(-a(n)).

A065493.name: Decimal expansion of the Feller-Tornier constant (1 + A065474)/2.

A065494.name: Number of (binary) bit strings in which no even length block of 0's is followed by an even length block of 1's.

A065495.name: Number of (binary) bit strings of length n in which an odd length block of 0's is followed by an odd length block of 1's.

A065496.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) is a nontrivial power, i.e., sigma(n) = a^b where a and b are greater than 1.

A065497.name: Number of (binary) bit strings of length n having at least one even length block of 0's followed by an even length block of 1's.
formula: G.f.: x^4/((1 - 2*x)*(1 - 3*x^2 - 2*x^3 + x^4)). [Corrected by _Georg Fischer_, May 15 2019]

A065498.name: Number of invertible n X n matrices mod 6 (i.e., over the ring Z_6).

A065499.name: Noninvertible 3 X 3 matrices over Z_n.
formula: a(n) = n^9 - A064767(n) = n^9 - n^9 * product (1-1/p^3)*(1-1/p^2)*(1-1/p) where the product is over all the primes p that divide n.

A065500.name: Number of distinct functions from a set with n^n elements to itself that can be defined naturally (in n) by typed lambda-calculus expressions.
formula: a(n) = lcm(seq(i, i=1..n))+n-1, except at n=0 (where the lcm is infinite).

A065501.name: Number of conjugacy classes in the group SL(2,Z_n) (see A000056).

A065502.name: Positive numbers divisible by 2 or 5; 1/n not purely periodic after decimal point.
formula: a(n) = 10*floor(n/6)+s(n mod 6)-floor(((n-1)mod 6)/5), where s(n) = n+1+floor((n+1)/3). - _Gary Detlefs_, Oct 05 2013

A065503.name: Let p(k) denote k-th prime; consider solutions (x,y) of Diophantine equation p(x+1)-6p(y)=1 (*), where p(x) belongs to A060213 and p(m)=(p(n)+1)/6; sequence gives values of x.

A065504.name: a(n+1) = a(n) + n + the number of a(k)'s <= n, 1 <= k <= n and a(1) = 1.

A065505.name: Let p(k) denote k-th prime; consider solutions (p(n),p(m)) of Diophantine equation p(p(n)+1)-6.p(p(m))=1 (*), where p(p(n)) belongs to A060213 and p(p(m))=(p(p(n))+1)/6; sequence gives values of p(n).

A065506.name: Number of (binary) bit strings of length n having an even length block of 0's followed by an odd length block of 1's.

A065507.name: Smallest prime q such that (p^q+1)/(p+1) is a prime, where p = prime(n).

A065508.name: Primes p such that p^2 - p + 1 is prime.

A065509.name: Primes p such that p^4 + p^3 + p^2 + p + 1 is prime.

A065510.name: Primes p such that p^4 - p^3 + p^2 - p + 1 is prime.

A065511.name: Let p(k) denote k-th prime; consider solutions (n,m) of the Diophantine system {p(p(n)+1)-p(p(n))=2, p(p(n))-6.p(p(m))=-1} (*); sequence gives values of m.

A065512.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) + 1 is prime.

A065513.name: Number of endofunctions of [n] with a cycle a->b->c->a and for all x in [n], some iterate f^k(x)=a.
formula: E.g.f.: T^3/3 where T=T(x) is Euler's tree function (see A000169).

A065515.name: Number of prime powers <= n.
formula: Partial sums of A010055. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Nov 22 2009
a(n) = 1 + Sum_{k=2..n} floor(2*A001222(k)/(tau(k^2)-1)) where tau is A000005(n). - _Anthony Browne_, May 17 2016

A065517.name: Numerator of n/(sum of the digits of n).

A065518.name: Denominator of n/(sum of the digits of n).

A065520.name: Numbers n with the property that if m is formed from n by dropping any number (possibly zero) of initial or final digits then there is a prime ending with m.

A065521.name: a(n) = floor(prime(n) / n) * n - prime(n) mod n.

A065522.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) and sigma(n+1) are nontrivial powers (A065496).

A065523.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) is a prime power (A025475).

A065528.name: Numbers n such that phi(n) is a nontrivial power b^c where b > 1 and c > 1.

A065530.name: If n is odd then a(n) = n, else a(n) = n*(n+2).

A065531.name: Number of palindromes in all base b representations for n, for 2<=b<=n.

A065535.name: Number of strongly perfect lattices in dimension n.

A065536.name: Number of strongly eutactic lattices in dimension n.

A065547.name: Triangle of Salie numbers.
formula: E.g.f.: Sum((n, k=0..inf) T(n, k) t^k x^(2n)/(2n)! = cosh(sqrt(1+4t) x/2)/ cosh(x/2).
Polynomial recurrences: x^n = Sum[0<=2i<=n, C(n, 2i)*H(n-i, x)]; (1/4+x)^n = Sum[m=0..n, C(2n, 2m)*(1/4)^(n-m)*H(m, x)].
Dumont/Zeng give a continued fraction and other formulas.
Triangle T(n, k) read by rows; given by [0, -1, -2, -4, -6, -9, -12, -16, ...] DELTA A000035, where DELTA is Deléham's operator defined in A084938.

A065549.name: a(1) = 1; for n > 1, a(n) = 2^((A000043(n) - 1)/2).
formula: log(n) is approximately log(sqrt(A000668(n)/2)). - _César Aguilera_, Nov 11 2018

A065551.name: Triangle of Faulhaber numbers (numerators) read by rows.
formula: sum(n>=0, k>=0, f(n, k)*t^k*x^(2*n+1)/(2*n+1)! ) is the expansion of (cosh(sqrt(1+4*t)*x/2)-cosh(x/2))/t/sinh(x/2).

A065553.name: Triangle of Faulhaber numbers (denominators) read by rows.
formula: sum(n>=0, k>=0, f(n, k)*t^k*x^(2*n+1)/(2*n+1)! ) is the expansion of (cosh(sqrt(1+4*t)*x/2)-cosh(x/2))/t/sinh(x/2).

A065555.name: Numbers n such that phi(phi(n)) = phi(sigma(n)) where phi is Euler's totient and sigma is the multiplicative sum-of-divisors function.

A065556.name: Numbers n such that sigma (phi ( n ) ) = sigma (sigma (n ) ) where phi is Euler's totient and sigma is the multiplicative sum-of-divisors function.

A065557.name: Solutions k of the equation phi(k) = phi(k-1) + phi(k-2). Also known as Phibonacci numbers.

A065558.name: Let G_n be the group of invertible 2 X 2 matrices mod n (sequence A000252). a(n) is the maximal degree of an irreducible representation of G_n.

A065559.name: Smallest k such that tau(n+k) = tau(k).

A065560.name: Let f(x,y) = floor((1+1/x)^y); a(n) is the smallest integer such that f(n,a(n)+1)/f(n,a(n)) = 1+1/n.

A065561.name: a(1) = 1; for n >= 2, a(n) = (d(n)-1)-th highest positive integer that equals no a(k), 1 <= k < n, where d(n) is the number of positive divisors of n, A000005(n).

formula: a(n) = A(n-1, 1) for the above Gandhi polynomials.

A065758.name: Numbers n divided by n - phi(n) in approximately the golden ratio, i.e., n such that for some r, n is an r-digit minimizer of abs(k / (k - EulerPhi(k)) - (golden ratio phi)).

A065759.name: For a number k of length L, let f(k) be the sum of the products of the first i digits of k multiplied by the last L-i digits, for i from 1 to L-1, e.g., f(1234) = 1*234 + 12*34 + 123*4 = 1134. Sequence gives k such that f(k) = k.

A065760.name: Concatenation of increasing number of alternating digits in base 2, starting with 1.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) * 2^n if n is even, (a(n-1) + 1) * 2^n - 1 if n is odd. - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Sep 18 2012

A065761.name: Concatenation of increasing number of alternating digits in base 2, starting with 0.
formula: a(1) = 0; a(n+1) = append n+1 0's or 1's (alternately) to a(n).

A065762.name: a(n) = (sum of first n primes)^2 + sum of (squares of first n primes).

A065763.name: Number of invertible Steinhaus matrices of order n.

A065764.name: Sum of divisors of square numbers.
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-1)*zeta(s-2)/zeta(2*s-2), inverse Mobius transform of A000082. - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 06 2011
Dirichlet convolution of A001157 by the absolute terms of A055615. Also the Dirichlet convolution of A048250 by A000290. - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 12 2011
a(n) = Sum_{d|n} d*Psi(d), where Psi is A001615. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Feb 25 2012
a(n) >= (n+1) * sigma(n) - n, where sigma is A000203, equality holds if n is in A000961. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Apr 21 2012
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ 5*Zeta(3) * n^3 / Pi^2. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 30 2019

A065765.name: Sum of divisors of twice square numbers.

A065766.name: Sum of divisors of twice a square number, divided by three.
formula: Multiplicative with a(2^e) = (4^(e+1)-1)/3 and a(p^e) = (p^(2*e+1)-1)/(p-1) for an odd prime p. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 01 2001

A065767.name: Intersection of A065764 and A065765: n such that x and y exist with sigma[x^2] = n = sigma[2*(y^2)].

A065769.name: Prime cascade: multiplicative with a(p(m)^k) = p(m-1) * p(m)^(k-1).

A065770.name: Number of prime cascades to reach 1, where a prime cascade (A065769) is multiplicative with a(p(m)^k) = p(m-1) * p(m)^(k-1).
formula: Inverse of primes, powers of 2 and primorials in sense that a(A000040(n))=n; a(A000079(n))=n; a(A002110(n))=n. If n>0: a(3^n)=n+1; a(2^n*3^k)=n+k; a(p(k)^n)=n+k-1; a(n!)=A022559(n).
a(1) = 0; and for n > 1, a(n) = 1 + A065769(n). - _Antti Karttunen_, Dec 31 2017

A065771.name: Prime powers n such that both tau(n^2) and sigma(n^2) are composite numbers.
formula: A000005(A025475(n)^2) and A000203(A025475(n)^2) are composite numbers.

A065772.name: Nontrivial prime powers n from A025475 such that tau[n^2] is prime but sigma[n^2] is a composite number.
formula: Numbers n such that A000005[A025475(n)^2] is prime but A000203[A025475(n)^2] is composite number.

A065773.name: Number of divisors of square of true prime powers arising in A065405.

A065774.name: Product of digits of n is equal to the sum of the prime factors of n, counted with multiplicity.

A065775.name: Array T read by diagonals: T(i,j)=least number of knight's moves on a chessboard (infinite in all directions) needed to move from (0,0) to (i,j).
formula: Cases 1-4 determine T in the 1st quadrant;
all other T(i,j) are easily obtained by symmetry.

A065776.name: a(n+1) is the next smallest square ending with a(n), initial term is 6.

A065777.name: a(1) = 4; for n > 1 is a(n) the square root of the smallest square > a(n-1)^2 with a(n-1)^2 forming its final digits.

A065778.name: a(1) = 16; for n > 1 is a(n) the smallest integer > 0 such that the concatenation a(n)a(n-1)...a(2)a(1) is a square.

A065780.name: a(1) = 5; for n > 1 is a(n) the square root of the smallest square > a(n-1)^2 with a(n-1)^2 forming its final digits.

A065781.name: a(1) = 25; for n > 1 is a(n) the smallest integer > 0 such that the concatenation a(n)a(n-1)...a(2)a(1) is a square.

A065782.name: a(1) = 36; for n > 1 is a(n) the smallest square > a(n-1) with a(n-1) forming its final digits.

A065783.name: a(1) = 6; for n > 1 is a(n) the square root of the smallest square > a(n-1)^2 with a(n-1)^2 forming its final digits.

A065784.name: a(1) = 36; for n > 1 is a(n) the smallest integer > 0 such that the concatenation a(n)a(n-1)...a(2)a(1) is a square.

A065785.name: a(1) = 49; for n > 1 is a(n) the smallest square > a(n-1) with a(n-1) forming its final digits.

A065786.name: a(1) = 7; for n > 1 is a(n) the square root of the smallest square > a(n-1)^2 with a(n-1)^2 forming its final digits.

A065787.name: a(1) = 49; for n > 1 is a(n) the smallest integer > 0 such that the concatenation a(n)a(n-1)...a(2)a(1) is a square.

A065788.name: a(1) = 64; for n > 1 is a(n) the smallest square > a(n-1) with a(n-1) forming its final digits.

A065789.name: a(1) = 8; for n > 1 is a(n) the square root of the smallest square > a(n-1)^2 with a(n-1)^2 forming its final digits.

A065790.name: a(1) = 64; for n > 1 is a(n) the smallest integer > 0 such that the concatenation a(n)a(n-1)...a(2)a(1) is a square.

A065791.name: a(1) = 81; for n > 1 is a(n) the smallest square > a(n-1) with a(n-1) forming its final digits.

A065792.name: a(1) = 9; for n > 1 is a(n) the square root of the smallest square > a(n-1)^2 with a(n-1)^2 forming its final digits.

A065793.name: a(1) = 81; for n > 1 is a(n) the smallest integer > 0 such that the concatenation a(n)a(n-1)...a(2)a(1) is a square.

A065794.name: Numbers n such that the sum of all possible subsets of the digits in n, excluding n itself, sums to n.

A065795.name: Number of subsets of {1,2,...,n} that contain the average of their elements.
formula: a(n) = (1/2)*Sum_{i=1..n} (f(i) - 1) where f(i) = (1/i) * Sum_{d | i and d is odd} 2^(i/d) * phi(d).

A065796.name: Alternating sum of digits of n^2.
formula: a(n) = n^2 mod 10 - n^2 mod 100 div 10 + n^2 mod 1000 div 100 - ...

A065797.name: Numbers n such that n^n - n + 1 is prime.

A065798.name: Numbers n such that n^n - n - 1 is prime.

A065799.name: Numbers k such that k^k + k! + k^2 + k + 1 is prime.

A065800.name: Numbers n which, for some r, are r-digit maximizers of n/phi(n).

A065802.name: How small is the squeezed n-gon? Let s0 be the side of a regular n-gon and s1 the side of the maximal n-gon which can be squeezed between the former and its circumcircle. The n-th entry in the sequence is floor(s0/s1).
formula: For n=odd: a(n) = floor((1+cos(Pi/n))/(1-cos(Pi/n))) For n=even: a(n) = floor( 2*(2/(tan(Pi/n))^2) + 1 )
a(n) = floor(4*n^2/Pi^2) - b(n) where b(n) is in {0,1,2}; 0 occurs only for odd n, while 2 occurs only for even n. - _Robert Israel_, Oct 24 2017

A065803.name: a(n) = (sigma_2(n) mod 2) * (sigma_2(n) mod 5). Residue-product modulo 2 and 5 of sum of square of divisors.

A065807.name: Squares with a smaller square as final digits.

A065808.name: Square of n has a smaller square as its final digits.

A065809.name: a(n) = smallest number m>n such that m is palindromic in base n and is not palindromic in bases b with 2 <= b < n.

A065810.name: Sorted positions of the elements of the quasicyclic group Z+(2a+1)/(2^b) [a > 0 and a < 2^(b-1), b > 0] at the ]0,1[ side of the Stern-Brocot Tree (A007305/A007306).

A065813.name: Least m such that (p^(2*m+1)-1)/(p-1) is a prime, where p = prime(n).

A065815.name: Numbers n such that initial n digits in decimal portion of the Euler-Mascheroni constant form a prime number.

A065816.name: Numbers k such that the alternating sum of digits of k^2 is 0.

A065817.name: Numbers n such that sigma_5(n)/sigma_1(n) is prime.

A065820.name: Numbers n such that sigma_6(n)/sigma_2(n) is prime.

A065821.name: a(n) is the first prime ending in exactly n 1's.

A065824.name: Smallest solution m to (n+1)*phi(m) = n*sigma(m), or -1 if no solution exists.

A065825.name: Smallest k such that n numbers may be picked in {1,...,k} with no three terms in arithmetic progression.

A065826.name: Triangle with T(n,k) = k*E(n,k) where E(n,k) are Eulerian numbers A008292.

A065827.name: Sum of squares of divisors of square numbers.
formula: Dirichlet g.f. zeta(s)*zeta(s-2)*zeta(s-4)/zeta(2s-4). Dirichlet convolution of A001159 by the arithmetic function with terms n^2*A008966(n). - _R. J. Mathar_, Mar 31 2011
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ 189 * Zeta(3) * Zeta(5) * n^5 / Pi^6. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 01 2019

A065828.name: Binary digits found in decimal expansion of Pi.

A065829.name: String formed from first n binary digits found in decimal expansion of Pi.

A065832.name: Numbers k such that the first k binary digits found in the base-10 expansion of Pi form a prime (when the decimal point is ignored).

A065833.name: Ternary digits found in decimal expansion of Pi.

A065834.name: String formed from first n ternary digits found in decimal expansion of Pi.

A065836.name: Quaternary digits found in decimal expansion of Pi.

A065837.name: String formed from first n quaternary digits found in decimal expansion of Pi.

A065840.name: Numbers n such that the first n quaternary digits found in the base-10 expansion of Pi form a prime (when the decimal point is ignored).

A065841.name: a(1) = 1; a(2) = 2; a(3) = 3; a(n) is concatenation of a(n-3), a(n-2) and a(n-1).

A065842.name: a(1) = 1; a(2) = 2; a(3) = 3; a(n) is concatenation of a(n-3), a(n-2) and a(n-1); the digits on the right of the first 3 (if any) are then swapped with the digits on the left.

A065843.name: Let u be any string of n digits from {0,1}; let f(u) = number of distinct primes, not beginning with 0, formed by permuting the digits of u; then a(n) = max_u f(u).

A065844.name: Let u be any string of n digits from {0,1,2}; let f(u) = number of distinct primes, not beginning with 0, formed by permuting the digits of u; then a(n) = max_u f(u).

A065845.name: Let u be any string of n digits from {0,...,3}; let f(u) = number of distinct primes, not beginning with 0, formed by permuting the digits of u; then a(n) = max_u f(u).

A065846.name: Let u be any string of n digits from {0,...,4}; let f(u) = number of distinct primes, not beginning with 0, formed by permuting the digits of u; then a(n) = max_u f(u).

A065847.name: Let u be any string of n digits from {0,...,5}; let f(u) = number of distinct primes, not beginning with 0, formed by permuting the digits of u; then a(n) = max_u f(u).

A065848.name: Let u be any string of n digits from {0,...,6}; let f(u) = number of distinct primes, not beginning with 0, formed by permuting the digits of u; then a(n) = max_u f(u).

A065849.name: Let u be any string of n digits from {0,...,7}; let f(u) = number of distinct primes, not beginning with 0, formed by permuting the digits of u; then a(n) = max_u f(u).

A065850.name: Let u be any string of n digits from {0,...,8}; let f(u) = number of distinct primes, not beginning with 0, formed by permuting the digits of u; then a(n) = max_u f(u).

A065851.name: Let u be any string of n digits from {0,...,9}; let f(u) = number of distinct primes, not beginning with 0, formed by permuting the digits of u; then a(n) = max_u f(u).

A065852.name: Let u be any string of 3 digits from {0,...,n-1}; let f(u) = number of distinct primes, not beginning with 0, formed by permuting the digits of u; then a(n) = max_u f(u).

A065853.name: Let u be any string of 4 digits from {0,...,n-1}; let f(u) = number of distinct primes, not beginning with 0, formed by permuting the digits of u; then a(n) = max_u f(u).

A065854.name: Smallest prime q such that (p^q-1)/(p-1) is a prime, where p = prime(n).

A065857.name: The (10^n)-th composite number.
formula: a(n) = 10^(n + n/log n + 2n/log^2 + 4n/log^3 n + O(n/log^4 n)). See Bojarincev for an asymptotic expansion. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 30 2013

A065858.name: m-th composite number c(m) = A002808(m), where m is the n-th prime number: a(n) = A002808(A000040(n)).

A065859.name: Remainder when the n-th prime is divided by the n-th composite number.

A065860.name: Remainder when the n-th composite number is divided by n.

A065861.name: Remainder when the n-th composite number is divided by pi(n), the number of primes not exceeding n.

A065862.name: Remainder when n-th composite number is divided by the number of nonprimes not exceeding n.

A065863.name: Remainder when n-th prime is divided by the number of nonprimes not exceeding n.
formula: a(n) = prime(n) mod (n - pi(n)) = A000040(n) mod A062298(n).

A065864.name: Remainder when n is divided by the number of nonprimes not exceeding n.
formula: a(n) = n mod (n-pi(n)) = n mod (n-A000720(n)) = n mod A062298(n).

A065865.name: a(n) is the least k such that nk - 1 and nk + 1 are both composite.

A065866.name: a(n) = n! * Catalan(n+1).
formula: E.g.f.: (1-2*x-sqrt(1-4*x))/(2*x^2) = (O.g.f. for A000108)^2 = B_2(x)^2 (cf. GKP reference).
The e.g.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = -2 + A(x) * (6*x - 2) + A'(x) * (4*x^2 - x). - _Michael Somos_, Apr 14 2015

A065867.name: Primes which are the sum of a prime number of consecutive primes.

A065868.name: Initial n digits in decimal portion of golden ratio phi (or tau) = (1 + sqrt 5)/2 form a prime number.

A065871.name: Numbers k such that usigma(k) + 1 is a prime.

A065872.name: Numbers k such that usigma(k) - 1 is a prime (cf. A034448).

A065873.name: Numbers k such that usigma(k) +-1 are twin primes, where usigma(k) is the sum of the unitary divisors of k (A034448).

A065876.name: a(n) is the smallest m > n such that n^2 + 1 divides m^2 + 1.

A065877.name: Non-Niven (or non-Harshad) numbers: numbers which are not a multiple of the sum of their digits.

A065878.name: Numbers which are not an integer multiple of their number of binary 1's.

A065879.name: Lowest positive number that is n times the number of 1's in its binary expansion, or 0 if no such number exists.

A065880.name: Largest positive number that is n times the number of 1's in its binary expansion, or 0 if no such number exists.

A065881.name: Ultimate modulo 10: right-hand nonzero digit of n.
formula: If n mod 10 = 0 then a(n) = a(n/10), otherwise a(n) = n mod 10.

A065882.name: Ultimate modulo 4: right-hand nonzero digit of n when written in base 4.
formula: If n mod 4 = 0 then a(n) = a(n/4), otherwise a(n) = n mod 4. a(n) = A065883(n) mod 4.
Fixed point of the morphism: 1 ->1231, 2 ->1232, 3 ->1233, starting from a(1) = 1. Sequence read mod 2 gives A035263. a(n) = A007913(n) mod 4. - _Philippe Deléham_, Mar 28 2004
G.f. g(x) satisfies g(x) = g(x^4) + (x + 2 x^2 + 3 x^3)/(1 - x^4). - _Bradley Klee_, Sep 12 2015

A065883.name: Remove factors of 4 from n (i.e., write n in base 4, drop final zeros, then rewrite in decimal).
formula: If n mod 4 = 0 then a(n) = a(n/4), otherwise a(n) = n.
Multiplicative with a(p^e) = 2^(e (mod 2)) if p = 2 and a(p^e) = p^e if p is an odd prime.
a(n) = A214392(n) if n mod 16 != 0. - _Peter Kagey_, Sep 02 2015
G.f. satisfies G(x) = G(x^4) + x/(1-x)^2 - 4 x^4/(1-x^4)^2. (End)

A065885.name: a(n)-1, a(n) and a(n)+1 form three consecutive integers that can be factored into Fibonacci numbers.
formula: Except for n = 1, 2, 4 and 7, a(n) is the square of a Fibonacci number.
From _Colin Barker_, Sep 30 2016: (Start) (based on the signature given in the link}
a(n) = 3*a(n-1) - a(n-2) - 2*(-1)^n for n >= 10. - _Greg Dresden_, May 18 2020

A065887.name: Smallest number whose square is divisible by n!.

A065888.name: a(n) = number of endofunctions on [n] with a 4-cycle a->b->c->d->a and for any x in [n], some iterate f^k(x) = a.
formula: E.g.f.: T^4/4 where T = T(x) is Euler's tree function (see A000169).

A065889.name: a(n) = number of unicyclic connected simple graphs whose cycle has length 4.
formula: E.g.f.: T^4/8, where T = T(x) is Euler's tree function (see A000169).

A065890.name: Number of composites less than the n-th prime.

A065893.name: Which composite number is the square of n? Index of n^2 in A002808.

A065897.name: The a(n)-th composite number is twice the n-th prime.

A065898.name: Which composite number is the product of first n primes (the n-th primorial number)?

A065899.name: a(n) is the index of the n-th compositorial number, A036691(n), in the sequence of composites (A002808).

A065900.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) = sigma(n-1) + sigma(n-2).

A065902.name: Smallest prime p such that n is a solution mod p of x^4 = 2, or 0 if no such prime exists.
formula: If n^4 - 2 has prime factors > n, then a(n) = smallest of these prime factors, else a(n) = 0.

A065903.name: Integers i > 1 for which there is no prime p such that i is a solution mod p of x^4 = 2.
formula: a(n) = n-th integer i such that i^4 - 2 has no prime factor > i.

A065904.name: Integers i > 1 for which there is one prime p such that i is a solution mod p of x^4 = 2.
formula: a(n) = n-th integer i such that i^4 - 2 has one prime factor > i.

A065905.name: Integers i > 1 for which there are two primes p such that i is a solution mod p of x^4 = 2.
formula: a(n) = n-th integer i such that i^4 - 2 has two prime factors > i.

A065906.name: Integers i > 1 for which there are three primes p such that i is a solution mod p of x^4 = 2.
formula: a(n) = n-th integer i such that i^4 - 2 has three prime factors > i.

A065907.name: First solution mod p of x^4 = 2 for primes p such that only two solutions exist.
formula: a(n) = first (least) solution mod p of x^4 = 2, where p is the n-th prime such that x^4 = 2 has only two solutions mod p, i.e. p is the n-th term of A007522.

A065908.name: Second solution mod p of x^4 = 2 for primes p such that only two solutions exist.
formula: a(n) = second (largest) solution mod p of x^4 = 2, where p is the n-th prime such that x^4 = 2 has only two solutions mod p, i.e. p is the n-th term of A007522.

A065909.name: First solution mod p of x^4 = 2 for primes p such that more than two solutions exist.
formula: a(n) = first (least) solution mod p of x^4 = 2, where p is the n-th prime such that x^4 = 2 has more than two solutions mod p, i.e. p is the n-th term of A014754.

A065910.name: Second solution mod p of x^4 = 2 for primes p such that more than two solution exists.
formula: a(n) = second solution mod p of x^4 = 2, where p is the n-th prime such that x^4 = 2 has more than two solutions mod p, i.e. p is the n-th term of A014754.

A065911.name: Third solution mod p of x^4 = 2 for primes p such that more than two solution exists.
formula: a(n) = third solution mod p of x^4 = 2, where p is the n-th prime such that x^4 = 2 has more than two solutions mod p, i.e. p is the n-th term of A014754.

A065912.name: Fourth solution mod p of x^4 = 2 for primes p such that more than two solution exists.
formula: a(n) = fourth solution mod p of x^4 = 2, where p is the n-th prime such that x^4 = 2 has more than two solutions mod p, i.e. p is the n-th term of A014754.

A065914.name: Number of primes in the interval [ 1/2 * q(n), 3/2 * q(n) - 1 ] where q(n) is prime(n)#, the n-th primorial.

A065916.name: Denominator of sigma(8*n^2)/sigma(4*n^2).
formula: a(n) = 2^s-1, with s = 2*A007814(n) + 3. Recurrence: a(2n) = 4a(n)+3, a(2n+1) = 7. - _Ralf Stephan_, Aug 22 2013

A065917.name: Boundaries of primorial intervals [1,3]; [3,9],[9,15]; [15,45], etc.
formula: a(n+1)= a(n)+q(j) for primorial q(j) < a(n+1) <= q(j+1)/2.

A065918.name: Decimal expansion of log(2 + sqrt(3)).
formula: Equals arccosh(2) since arccosh(x) = log(x + sqrt(x^2 - 1)). - _Stanislav Sykora_, Nov 01 2013

A065919.name: Bessel polynomial y_n(4).
formula: Recurrence relation: a(0) = 1, a(1) = 5, a(n) = 4*(2*n-1)*a(n-1) + a(n-2) for n >= 2. Sequence A143412(n) satisfies the same recurrence relation.
G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k)= 1 - x - 4*x*(k+1)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 17 2013
E.g.f.: d/dx( exp(x*c(2*x)) ) = 1 + 5*x + 61*x^2/2! + 1225*x^3/3! + ..., where c(x) = (1 - sqrt(1 - 4*x))/(2*x) is the g.f. of the Catalan numbers A000108. (End)

A065923.name: Bessel polynomial y_n(-3).
formula: a(n) = -(6*n-3)*a(n-1) + a(n-2) for n >= 2. - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 17 2013
G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k)= 1 - x + 3*x*(k+1)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 17 2013
a(n) = (1/2)_{n} * (-3)^n *hypergeometric1f1(-n; -2n; -2/3), where (a)_{n} is the Pochhammer symbol.

A065924.name: Numbers n such that 1/n starts with n, after excluding leading zeros.

A065925.name: Smallest k such that sopf(n+k) = sopf(k), where sopf = A008472.

A065926.name: Index values for new maxima in A065925.

A065928.name: (x,y) = (a(n),a(n+1)) are the solutions of (t(x)+t(y))/(1+xy)) = t(2) = 3, where t(n) denotes the n-th triangular number t(n) = n(n+1)/2.

A065929.name: (x,y) = (a(n),a(n+1)) are the solutions of (t(x)+t(y))/(1+xy)) = t(3) = 6, where t(n) denotes the n-th triangular number t(n) = n(n+1)/2.

A065930.name: (x,y) = (a(n),a(n+1)) are the solutions of (t(x)+t(y))/(1+xy)) = t(4) = 10, where t(n) denotes the n-th triangular number t(n) = n(n+1)/2.

A065931.name: Triangle of coefficients of Bessel polynomials {y_n(x)}'.

A065932.name: Index values for new maxima in sequence A007365.

A065934.name: Permutation of N induced by the order-preserving bijection QuQR1toQuQR2 on rationals.

A065935.name: Permutation of N induced by the order-preserving bijection QuQR2toQuQR1 on rationals.

A065936.name: a(n) is the integer (reduced squarefree) under the square root obtained when the inverse of a variant of Minkowski's question mark function is applied to the n-th ratio A007305(n+1)/A007306(n+1) in the left-hand subtree of Stern-Brocot tree and zero when it results a rational value.

A065937.name: a(n) is the integer (reduced squarefree) under the square root obtained when the inverse of Minkowski's question mark function is applied to the n-th ratio A007305(n+1)/A047679(n-1) in the full Stern-Brocot tree and zero when it results a rational value.

A065938.name: Position of sqrt(n) in the mapping N2QuQR1 given in A065936.

A065939.name: Position of sqrt(n) in the mapping N2QuQR2 given in A065937.

A065940.name: Integers of the form bc/a + ac/b + ab/c, where a,b,c are positive integers.

A065941.name: T(n,k) = binomial(n-floor((k+1)/2), floor(k/2)). Triangle read by rows, for 0 <= k <= n.
formula: As a square array read by antidiagonals, this is given by T1(n, k) = binomial(floor(n/2) + k, k). - _Paul Barry_, Mar 11 2003
Triangle is a reflection of that in A066170 (absolute values). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Feb 16 2004
Recurrences: T(k, 0) = 1, T(k, n) = T(k-1, n) + T(k-2, n-2), or T(k, n) = T(k-1, n) + T(k-1, n-1) if n even, T(k-1, n-1) if n odd. - _Ralf Stephan_, May 17 2004
G.f.: sum[n, sum[k, T(k, n)x^ky^n]] = (1+xy)/(1-y-x^2y^2). sum[n>=0, T(k, n)y^n] = y^k/(1-y)^[k/2]. - _Ralf Stephan_, May 17 2004
T(n, k) = A108299(n, k)*A087960(k) = abs(A108299(n, k)). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jun 01 2005
For n > 1: T(n, k) = T(n-2, k) + T(n-1, k), 1 < k < n. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 24 2013

A065942.name: Central column of triangle A065941.
formula: a(n+1) = Sum_{k=0..ceiling(n/2)} binomial(n+k, k). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 06 2004
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n-1+k, k). - _Paul Barry_, Jul 06 2004
a(2n-1) = binomial(3n-3,n-1); a(2n) = binomial(3n-2,n-1). - _John Molokach_, Jul 08 2013
G.f.: A(x) = x*(d/dx)[log(S(x)-1)] = x*[(d/dx) S(x)]/[S(x)-1], where S(x) is the g.f. of A047749. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Jun 12 2014.

A065943.name: Triangle of coefficients of Bessel polynomials {y_n(x)}''.

A065944.name: Bessel polynomial {y_n}''(-1).
formula: a(n) = 2*n*(n-1)*(1/2)_{n}*(-2)^(n - 1)* hypergeometric1f1(2 - n, -2*n, -2), where (a)_{n} is the Pochhammer symbol.

A065946.name: Bessel polynomial {y_n}''(-2).
formula: a(n) = 4*n*(n - 1)*(1/2)_{n}*(-4)^(n - 2)*hypergeometric1f1[(2-n, -2*n, -1), where (a)_{n} is the Pochhammer symbol.

A065947.name: Bessel polynomial {y_n}''(3).
formula: a(n) = 4*n*(n - 1)*(1/2)_{n}*6^(n - 2)*hypergeometric1F1[(2-n, -2*n, 2/3), where (a)_{n} is the Pochhammer symbol.

A065948.name: Bessel polynomial {y_n}''(-3).
formula: a(n) = 4*n*(n - 1)*(1/2)_{n}*(-6)^(n - 2)* hypergeometric1f1(2 - n; -2*n; -2/3), where (a)_{n} is the Pochhammer symbol.

A065950.name: Bessel polynomial {y_n}'''(1).
formula: a(n) = 48*binomial(n, 3)*(1/2)_{n}*(2)^(n - 3)* hypergeometric1f1(3 - n, -2*n, 2), where (a)_{n} is the Pochhammer symbol. - _G. C. Greubel_, Aug 15 2017

A065951.name: Bessel polynomial {y_n}'''(-1).
formula: a(n) = 48*binomial(n,3)*(1/2)_{n}*(-2)^(n - 3)*hypergeometric1f1(3-n, -2*n, -2), where (a)_{n} is the Pochhammer symbol. - _G. C. Greubel_, Aug 15 2017

A065954.name: Nearest integer to (-1)^n*n!*(E(n,2)-E(n,1)*E(n-1,1)) where E(n,x) = Sum_{k=0..n} (-1)^k*x^k/k!.

A065957.name: This is the case k = 3 of the number of orbits of the group of units of Z/(n) acting naturally on the k-subsets of Z/(n).

A065958.name: a(n) = n^2*Product_{distinct primes p dividing n} (1+1/p^2).
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p^(2*e) + p^(2*e-2). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 09 2001
a(n) = n^2 * Sum_{d|n} mu(d)^2/d^2 - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 07 2002
Inverse Euler transform of n*A156733(n). - _Paul D. Hanna_ and _Vladeta Jovovic_, Feb 14 2009
a(n) = J_4(n)/J_2(n) = A059377(n)/A007434(n), where J_k is the k-th Jordan Totient Function. (End)
Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-2)/zeta(2s). Dirichlet convolution of A008966 and A000290. - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 10 2011
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} mu(k)^2*x^k*(1 + x^k)/(1 - x^k)^3. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 24 2018
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} psi(gcd(n,k))*n/gcd(n,k), where psi(n) = A001615(n).

A065959.name: a(n) = n^3*Product_{distinct primes p dividing n} (1+1/p^3).
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p^(3*e)+p^(3*e-3). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 09 2001
a(n) = J_6(n)/J_3(n) = A069091(n)/A059376(n). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Aug 22 2010
Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-3)/zeta(2*s). Dirichlet convolution of A008966 and A000578. - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 10 2011
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} mu(k)^2*x^k*(1 + 4*x^k + x^(2*k))/(1 - x^k)^4. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 24 2018

A065960.name: a(n) = n^4*Product_{distinct primes p dividing n} (1+1/p^4).
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p^(4*e)+p^(4*e-4). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 09 2001
a(n) = n^4 * Sum_{d|n} mu(d)^2/d^4. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 07 2002
a(n) = J_8(n)/J_4(n) = A069093(n)/A059377(n), where J_k is the k-th Jordan Totient Function. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Aug 29 2010
Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-4)/zeta(2*s). - _R. J. Mathar_, Jun 06 2011

A065963.name: Smallest number which is digitally balanced in n bases, for 2 <= base b <= a(n).

A065964.name: a(n) is the smallest k such that (k^3 + 1)/(n^3 + 1) is an integer > 1.

A065968.name: a(n) = n * Sum_{primes p dividing n} (1 - 1/p).

A065969.name: a(n) = n^2 * Sum_{primes p dividing n} (1 + 1/p^2).

A065970.name: a(n) = n^2 * Sum_{primes p dividing n} (1 - 1/p^2).

A065973.name: Denominators in an asymptotic expansion of Ramanujan.

A065976.name: Consecutive terms of A065966 which are also consecutive integers.

A065977.name: Numbers n such that n divides the number formed by the first n decimal digits of e (A039920(n)).

A065978.name: For even n >= 4, let f(n) = A066285(n/2) be the minimal difference between primes p and q whose sum is n. Such an n is in the sequence if f(n) > f(m) for all even m with 4 <= m < n.

A065980.name: Inverse binomial transform of [1^1,2^2,3^3,...], shifted right by one index.
formula: O.g.f.: Sum_{n>0} (n*x/(1+x))^n. E.g.f.: int(-exp(-x)*LambertW(-x)/(1+LambertW(-x))^3/x, x). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 12 2003

A065981.name: Best approximation of the remainder in the zeta(4) series using the remainder in the zeta(3) series.

A065984.name: Volume (multiplied by 3) of polyhedron formed by points (i,j,k) in Z^3 with i^2+j^2+k^2 = n.

A065985.name: Numbers n such that d(n) / 2 is prime, where d(n) = number of divisors of n.

A065986.name: Numbers n such that Sigma(n) = EulerPhi(n+1) + EulerPhi(n) + EulerPhi(n-1).

A065987.name: Numbers n such that the first n binary digits of Pi expressed in decimal forms a prime.

A065989.name: The first n ternary digits of Pi expressed in decimal forms a prime.

A065991.name: The first n base-4 digits of Pi expressed in decimal forms a prime.

A065993.name: The first n base-6 digits of Pi (A004605) expressed in decimal forms a prime.

A065997.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) / n is prime.

A065998.name: Concatenate n and number of divisors of n.

A066000.name: Size of smallest directed 1-covering code of length n.
